WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.360
&gt;&gt; Ted Widmer: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:21.660
My name is Ted Widmer.

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:25.330
I'm the brand new director of
the Kluge Center and really happy

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:26.630
to welcome all of you here.

00:00:26.630 --> 00:00:28.960
Some of you came a great distance.

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:33.770
And it's an honor to host this
important event today organized

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:36.110
by Toyin Falola.

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:38.260
I came from not all that far away.

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:42.170
I came from the city of Providence,
Rhode Island where there is a small

00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:48.040
but thriving Liberian community
and a growing abundance

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:53.120
of African restaurants, which
one of my sorrows at moving

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:55.440
to Washington is I don't know
the local restaurants as well

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:57.680
as I did where I come from.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:00.240
But in our old northeastern city,

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:04.610
this new immigrant population
constituted a really important

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:06.930
source of vitality.

00:01:06.930 --> 00:01:10.630
So we're all looking forward
to this conference today.

00:01:10.630 --> 00:01:15.020
And I want to thank Toyin
Falola for organizing it.

00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:19.030
I also want to pause briefly to
acknowledge my-- I joked yesterday,

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:23.090
my predecessor's predecessor's
predecessor's predecessor,

00:01:23.090 --> 00:01:27.210
Carolyn Brown who is
here with us as well.

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:31.710
The Kluge Center was created
with a gift in the year 2000

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:35.280
from John W. Kluge to
the Library of Congress.

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:38.940
It's still the largest gift that
ever has come to the Library

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:42.750
of Congress and it is a center
for scholars doing research

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:45.940
and for public events
such as this one.

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:48.610
And we're so grateful to have Toyin

00:01:48.610 --> 00:01:51.870
in our community which
he is deeply in.

00:01:51.870 --> 00:01:53.820
He serves the Kluge
Center in many ways.

00:01:53.820 --> 00:01:56.350
He's on the Scholars Council

00:01:56.350 --> 00:02:00.180
which is a very distinguished
board appointed by the librarian

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:02.940
of congress to give
advice on a range

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:05.970
of scholarly issues
to the librarian.

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:10.000
But he's also very much
among us on a daily basis.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.300
He has an office down the hall.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:15.160
He comes to all of our events
and we're really grateful

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:17.510
to him personally, as
well as professionally

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:20.220
for all that he brings to us.

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:23.760
Toyin is a professor
at University of Texas

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:27.550
and specifically he's the Jacob
and Frances Sanger Mossiker Chair

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:31.750
in the Humanities and University
Distinguished Teaching Professor

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:33.640
at UT Austin.

00:02:33.640 --> 00:02:36.330
He's also a fellow of the
Nigerian Academy of Letters,

00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:39.650
a fellow of the Historical
Society of Nigeria,

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:42.620
the author of numerous books
including "Violence in Nigeria:

00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:45.970
The Crisis of Religious
Politics and Secular Ideologies",

00:02:45.970 --> 00:02:49.160
"the Power of African
Cultures", and "Nationalism

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:50.700
and African Intellectuals".

00:02:50.700 --> 00:02:53.810
He's also the series
editor of "Rochester Studies

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:57.150
in African History and the
Diaspora" and the series editor

00:02:57.150 --> 00:03:00.750
of "Global Africa" by
Routledge, and also series editor

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:05.090
of "African Histories and
Modernities" by Palgrave Macmillan.

00:03:05.090 --> 00:03:06.710
Actually as I continue to read,

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:10.180
I see he's series editors
of a few more.

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:13.130
"Carolina Studies on
Africa and the Black World"

00:03:13.130 --> 00:03:16.410
and "African Identities" with
Cambridge University Press

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.180
and he's the co-editor
of the "Journal

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:23.040
of African Economic History"
and the "Yoruba Studies Review".

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:25.710
And he is well known to
all of you here today

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:27.390
and he has personally
invited you here.

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:30.360
So he is the person you
really should listen

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.670
to to get things underway.

00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:35.710
But I'm personally very happy to
introduce him and to thank him

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:37.160
for all he does for
the Kluge Center.

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:39.510
So please welcome Toyin Falola.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:44.500
[ Applause ]

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:55.640
&gt;&gt; Toyin Falola: It's a
pleasure for me to be here.

