00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:23.660
of Higher Education,
the Time Magazine,

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:27.010
Global Post and many others.

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:35.360
And he's done three major
books, all very well respected,

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:38.790
including the finalist
for the Herskovits and is

00:07:38.790 --> 00:07:45.490
at the moment working on
what Nigerian Muslims think

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:50.740
about Imperial Britain in the
first half of the 20th century.

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.800
Please join me in welcoming
all of them.

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:55.600
You want to take a seat?

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.450
[ Applause ]

00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:00.890
Please come and take your seat.

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:02.620
Let me start.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:10.110
And my PowerPoint is
there but my interest

00:08:10.110 --> 00:08:13.670
in this topic has expanded
very widely.

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:22.860
And last year, when I gave
the usual presidential speech

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:25.370 position:56%
of the African Studies Association--

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:28.630
By the way, those of you who are
involved with the association,

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:31.120
one of the reasons why people
don't want to serve is because of

00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:36.570
that speech, because it's
so difficult to write.

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:41.580
What I did was to map out how a
new discipline can emerge arising

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:43.160
from this topic.

00:08:43.160 --> 00:08:49.560
I was taking a lot of risk because
for that discipline to be created,

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:53.770
we have to fragment what
is called Black Studies

00:08:53.770 --> 00:09:01.540 position:56%
or fragment African-American
Studies and either drew an insertion

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:09.090
of the new field that I proposed
which was very well received.

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:15.200
Turn it into a separate self-field
on its own in the academy.

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:21.170
And I have been-- like an onion,

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:25.440
I've been peeling this
project in various dimensions.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:32.670
And I ran into one of the Kluge
staff in the train one day

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:35.600
when I was going for an interview.

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:42.380 position:56%
And since September, I've been doing
a lot of interviews in three states,

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:44.940
in Virginia, Baltimore and DC.

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:48.840
I thought I'll be able
to report on this

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:53.410
but they're crunching all
this data for me in Austin.

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:56.950
But I've been able to
cover associations.

00:09:56.950 --> 00:10:00.050
I'm now on comfortable
ground talking

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.880
about immigrant associations.

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:08.340
Unlike the big state of Texas, it's
so much easier to do research here

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:14.170
because of the density and the
nearness of all of the spaces.

00:10:14.170 --> 00:10:20.030
And I'll be reporting on
this data in due course.

00:10:20.030 --> 00:10:25.000
Is there a way I can
control it from here, sir?

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:26.310
&gt;&gt; The thing right next to you.

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:27.850
&gt;&gt; Toyin Falola: Where is it?

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:29.150
Oh, this one?

00:10:29.150 --> 00:10:30.450
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:10:30.450 --> 00:10:31.750
&gt;&gt; Toyin Falola: OK.

00:10:31.750 --> 00:10:38.910
So, I've been preceded in
this by a variety of scholars.

00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:46.740
The trouble is that many of
them are based on conjectures,

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:54.420
in which they do personal
reflections.

00:10:54.420 --> 00:11:00.180
And the reason is the
options for quantitative data,

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:02.440
the options are very limited.

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:05.000
We can rely on the
limited census data

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.350
by the federal government
that exists.

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:13.310 position:56%
And then we can do sample data which
we can collect from specific places

00:11:13.310 --> 00:11:21.380
like in Western campuses
which I've done.

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:24.240
We can-- And for instance
we have figures

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:27.910
to say how many Africans
scholars at yield?

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:29.210
That is available.

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:30.810
That's not a problem.

00:11:30.810 --> 00:11:33.480
Or how many, you know,
students that are white?

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:35.410
That one we can do.

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:41.030
Or we can do specific research and
we can just take a narrow topic

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:44.070
and then they answer
specific questions.

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:46.140
That we can do.

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:54.090
And then you have a variety
of official categorization

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.890
that we can follow up on.

00:11:56.890 --> 00:12:01.420
So, I've gone beyond those to do
what is called snowballing samples.

00:12:01.420 --> 00:12:07.590 position:56%
I've interviewed various
locations, Houston, Dallas, Chicago.

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:12.490 position:56%
I was to go to Minnesota this summer
but it didn't work out because if--

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:18.310
I do not know how many of you are
following this story which a number

00:12:18.310 --> 00:12:22.610
of people from Somalia, some young
people, there are four of them,

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:25.280
who are arrested for joining ISIS.

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:27.500
And the community became very angry

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:33.830
that some members reveal
the identity of these kids,

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:41.460
and there's a lot of tension
on that to cancel that project.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:46.540
So in doing snowballing
samples, there's no time for me

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:52.060
to explain these limitations but it
has been very effective in trying

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:59.840
to see how a new set of data
can compliment existing ones.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:02.600
Here are the problems.

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:10.330
We have double counting, double
counting in which children born

00:13:10.330 --> 00:13:15.070
in the US and children born in
Africa, parent's identification

00:13:15.070 --> 00:13:17.730
of children's nationality
are very complicated.

00:13:17.730 --> 00:13:23.950
And double counting in so
many snowballing samples,

00:13:23.950 --> 00:13:29.510
the percentage is very high,
and also self-identification.

00:13:29.510 --> 00:13:31.600
By self-identification I mean

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:37.730
that somebody can say she's
American but she's also Nigerian.

00:13:37.730 --> 00:13:44.690
And accounting for that
self-identification is

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:46.310
very difficult.

00:13:46.310 --> 00:13:51.290
Even universities, it
has been very difficult.

00:13:51.290 --> 00:13:55.720
Part of the complication is
issues around dual citizenship,

00:13:55.720 --> 00:14:00.120
in which a person like
me, I carry two passports.

00:14:00.120 --> 00:14:03.140
When I'm leaving the US
I use Nigerian passport,

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:05.890
when I'm coming back
I use the US passport.

00:14:05.890 --> 00:14:10.460
And sometimes I have a third one
which is a diplomatic passport.

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:18.630 position:56%
So, that notion of dual citizenship,
whether it's a federal census

00:14:18.630 --> 00:14:23.190
or the ACLS, has created
its own complications.

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:27.900
Then you have the tendency
for naturalized Americans

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:32.210
to also call themselves
Africans so that this--

00:14:32.210 --> 00:14:36.960
it disconnect both in
the official figures.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:41.070
I know that figures between
citizenship by birth,

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:46.050
citizenship by naturalization,
and what people see.

00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:50.420
Then you have how ethnicities
define itself.

00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:56.070
In many African ethnicities, you
claim the birth place of your dad.

00:14:56.070 --> 00:15:02.900 position:56%
So if you are to go to an American
campus and you run to a negro person

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:07.670
who has never left the US,
the student may tell you he

00:15:07.670 --> 00:15:10.590
or she is evil but he has never--

00:15:10.590 --> 00:15:13.430
he or she may not have
left the country.

00:15:13.430 --> 00:15:16.100
That's not uncommon.

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:22.880
And those complications
make it extremely difficult

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:26.970
to use many of these samples.

00:15:28.150 --> 00:15:35.270 position:56%
In Dallas this summer, I was looking
at kids who got into drug problems,

00:15:35.270 --> 00:15:41.430 position:56%
and parents who are trying to adjust
the citizenship definition based

00:15:41.430 --> 00:15:44.050
on another variable of shame.

00:15:44.050 --> 00:15:48.220
So, then you have-- which you have

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:52.540
for all immigrant populations
undocumented labor.

00:15:52.540 --> 00:16:00.090
So if we go by official figures,
this is the US figures now.

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:09.910
And they tend to be lower than
what alternative sources tell us.

00:16:09.910 --> 00:16:21.600
In 1960, 33,000 Africans, in 1970,
80,000, we need to put that 1%

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:25.850
of the total population,
and in 2007, 1.4 million.

00:16:25.850 --> 00:16:30.950
The figure expanded in
the '70s for two reasons.

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:40.990
First, preference expanded as
people began to come to the US.

00:16:40.990 --> 00:16:46.490 position:56%
People who used to come to the US do
so because they can speak English.

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:49.950
And they tend to go to
former colonial masters.

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:51.880
People in Angola will
go to Portugal.

00:16:51.880 --> 00:16:54.380 position:56%
People in Senegal will go to France.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:17:01.020
That's very common because if
language is a problem in migration,

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:05.100
if you can't speak the
language, it's difficult--

00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:09.770
adjustments become difficult
and insertion becomes difficult.

00:17:09.770 --> 00:17:15.820
But as European economy
enters into this problem,

00:17:15.820 --> 00:17:17.780
they began to come
here in large number.

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:20.000
So today, for instance, at Harlem,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.340
there were a large
number of Senegalese.

00:17:22.340 --> 00:17:24.680 position:56%
They've created a Senegalese colony.

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:29.520
And then you have the crisis in the
'80s in Liberia, Ethiopia, Somalia

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:32.970
and Sudan, special
category of asylum.

00:17:32.970 --> 00:17:37.300
And in this special category
of asylum, more Africans came,

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:42.400
and in this asylum, they
changed the dynamics of location.

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:46.250
We know those who come voluntarily,
where they stay in the US.

00:17:46.250 --> 00:17:48.030
But with respect to asylum,

00:17:48.030 --> 00:17:50.160
the federal government
dictates where they go.

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.680
So that's why you now
find Africans in Dakota.

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:55.840
On their own they won't
go to Dakota.

00:17:55.840 --> 00:17:57.570
It's just not going
to work for them.

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:03.570
So by 2022, according to
the US federal figures,

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:07.800
there'll be 3 million
Africans living in the country.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:09.360
Is that a big number?

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:12.870
Well, some people would say
it's a small number relative

00:18:12.870 --> 00:18:17.110
to the rest of them, foreign bond.

00:18:17.110 --> 00:18:19.350
We've been able also
to break distance

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:21.930
down into where people come from.

00:18:21.930 --> 00:18:28.330
With West Africa, having
almost 29%, Northern Africa 17,

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:36.120
Eastern Africa following
and then North Africa.

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:42.060 position:56%
And the largest populations are from
Nigeria and Ghana, Ethiopia, Kenya,

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:44.740
