00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:07.530
So, the classic African migration
story has been told in the idiom

00:33:07.530 --> 00:33:12.980
of economic [inaudible] and of
destitution and displacement.

00:33:12.980 --> 00:33:16.080
Many scholars and observers
advance economic pressure

00:33:16.080 --> 00:33:19.400
and other involuntary
factors as the primary drivers

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:24.380
of African migratory itineraries,
especially when the migration is

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:27.330
from Africa to Euro-America.

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:33.200
In this spring, African migrants
in America are economic refugees.

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:37.910
Voluntary strategic migration
to America is often buried

00:33:37.910 --> 00:33:41.840
under this paradigm of
forced exile and escape

00:33:41.840 --> 00:33:45.520
from imminent death or destitution.

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:49.260
This overarching motive of economic
and personal danger is extended

00:33:49.260 --> 00:33:52.560
to African professionals who
relocates to America as part

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:54.790
of what's called as--

00:33:54.790 --> 00:33:58.410
have lamentably called
the African brain drain.

00:33:58.410 --> 00:34:02.100
It is also applied to an
increasingly strategic

00:34:02.100 --> 00:34:06.750
and voluntary group of
African migrants to America,

00:34:06.750 --> 00:34:11.090
Africans whose migration
stories hardly conform or fitting

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:15.020
to the familiar paradigm of
escape and economic desperation.

00:34:15.020 --> 00:34:19.640
On the line that notion that
Africans are migrating away

00:34:19.640 --> 00:34:22.640
from their continent
for economic refuge

00:34:22.640 --> 00:34:25.030
in America is an understanding
of Africa--

00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:29.720
African migration as a novel
phenomenon, or as a new phenomenon,

00:34:29.720 --> 00:34:34.200
a modern event threatening the
demographic and economic fates

00:34:34.200 --> 00:34:38.050
of both the origin and
destination of such migration.

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:41.770
It is sustained-- This idea is--

00:34:41.770 --> 00:34:45.890
This belief or this argument is
sustained by illusion of Africans

00:34:45.890 --> 00:34:50.220
as traditionally on adventures, and
people who can only be separated

00:34:50.220 --> 00:34:54.620
from their homelands by
existential pressures.

00:34:54.620 --> 00:34:59.290
The truth, however, is that much
as African migration to America

00:34:59.290 --> 00:35:03.430 position:56%
and other countries of the global
note has accelerated in recent times

00:35:03.430 --> 00:35:08.000
and has indeed been affected or
induced by economic collapse,

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:11.630
dysfunction and crisis,
voluntary migration

00:35:11.630 --> 00:35:16.290
to far-flung lands has always been
a defining social characteristic

00:35:16.290 --> 00:35:18.040
of African societies.

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:20.120
And I'm a historian.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:24.420
I should know this, and we can
talk about this more in the Q&amp;A.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:30.000
This voluntary strategic migration
has often occurred alongside

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.160
involuntary ones.

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:35.740
But it has often been
overshadowed by stories of dramatic

00:35:35.740 --> 00:35:39.840
and violent removal
or escape from Africa.

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:43.110
Given this backdrop, I would
like to introduce and argue

00:35:43.110 --> 00:35:46.820
and alternative thesis of
African migration to American.

00:35:46.820 --> 00:35:51.390
One that will I argue become even
more relevant in the coming decades

00:35:51.390 --> 00:35:53.140
as the mobility of skilled

00:35:53.140 --> 00:35:58.060
and talented workers increasingly
defy international borders.

00:35:58.060 --> 00:36:02.550
This thesis may not explain
the majority of cases

00:36:02.550 --> 00:36:06.540
of African migration to America but
it is increasingly proven useful

00:36:06.540 --> 00:36:10.250
as a way to understand newer
generations of migrants.

00:36:10.250 --> 00:36:12.670
My thesis here is quite simple.

00:36:12.670 --> 00:36:17.090
There is a motivational shift
occurring in the familiar story

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:19.450
of African migration to America.

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:24.180
It shift away from the
economic refugee paradigm.

00:36:24.180 --> 00:36:28.560
African migrations to America
are not always attributable

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.760
to economic reasons.

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:36.630
An increasing number of African
immigrants resist this category

00:36:36.630 --> 00:36:39.770
of economic refugee.

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:42.110
They resist the category
of economic refugee.

00:36:42.110 --> 00:36:48.170
More and more Africans self-- more
and more Africans, self-selected

00:36:48.170 --> 00:36:51.680
and well-educated are relocating
to America from their homelands

00:36:51.680 --> 00:36:57.160
in Africa not to escape poverty
or danger, but for adventure

00:36:57.160 --> 00:37:02.270
and the pursuit of intangible
psychosocial conveniences.

00:37:02.270 --> 00:37:06.890
This migratory process outside the
refugee paradigm has been going

00:37:06.890 --> 00:37:09.840
on for a long time and has
been growing in proportion

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:12.270
to the overall growth
in African migration

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:14.930
to America in recent decades.

00:37:14.930 --> 00:37:18.570
Yet, it has gone unrecognized
because of the long terms

00:37:18.570 --> 00:37:21.950
on the part of Americans
and Africans alike

00:37:21.950 --> 00:37:27.710
to highlight migratory motivations
outside of the refugee frame work.

00:37:27.710 --> 00:37:30.700
These were long terms to see
the African migrant outside

00:37:30.700 --> 00:37:36.790
of the refugee narrative stems from
multiple factors, I would argue.

00:37:36.790 --> 00:37:40.480
The trope of refuge and
induced exile sustains

00:37:40.480 --> 00:37:46.850
for many Americans the avuncular
humanitarian gaze on Africans.

00:37:46.850 --> 00:37:50.280
It enables them to assume
that self-defining position

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:53.940
of helper, nurturer and savior.

00:37:53.940 --> 00:37:57.810
Americans' sense of their
paternal mission works only

00:37:57.810 --> 00:38:01.180
by imagining the African
migrant as someone in need

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:05.160
of American paternal attention.

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:08.990
Paternalistic American attitudes
towards African immigrants walk

00:38:08.990 --> 00:38:12.780
better when the migrant
is theorized as a refugee

00:38:12.780 --> 00:38:14.950
and as a displaced hopeless

00:38:14.950 --> 00:38:20.490
and helpless basket case needing
the help of good natured Americans.

00:38:20.490 --> 00:38:24.820
For Africans, including migrants,
sustaining the refugee narrative

00:38:24.820 --> 00:38:29.130
and suppressing migratory stories
outside of it is a strategic effort

00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:34.660
to leverage the humanitarian
"White savior complex" of Americans

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:40.450
to obtain empathy, legalization
and access to resources in America.

00:38:42.530 --> 00:38:47.140
The logical endpoint of my argument
about recognizing the importance

00:38:47.140 --> 00:38:49.600
of psychosocial motivations
is simple.

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:53.610
Africans are not very different
from other peoples of the world,

00:38:53.610 --> 00:38:56.780
and this is a point that
Professor Falola made earlier.

00:38:56.780 --> 00:39:00.340
Like Europeans, Americans,
Asians, and others,

00:39:00.340 --> 00:39:03.420
Africans do not migrate
only because of poverty,

00:39:03.420 --> 00:39:06.090
hardship destitution
and helplessness.

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:10.710 position:56%
They also migrate because migrations
sometimes make you feel better

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:12.010
about yourself.

00:39:12.010 --> 00:39:16.340
Sometimes migration is,
to put it quite simply,

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:20.750
its own justification,
its own reward.

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:24.000
It satisfies an innate
human psychosocial desire

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.610
to explore the unfamiliar,
the other,

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:30.610
the distant, and the different.

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:33.030
For those who could
afford to migrate or those

00:39:33.030 --> 00:39:36.360
who can afford migration, spend
in a lifetime in one corner

00:39:36.360 --> 00:39:38.670
of the world is unappealing.

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:43.030
Many Africans are in this category
and their story is quite important.

00:39:43.030 --> 00:39:46.140
Well, this story goes untold
because there's little appetite

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:48.450
for it in the West, in America.

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:54.140
To advance an alternative thesis
of African migration to America,

00:39:54.140 --> 00:39:57.850
especially one that embraces a
more universal generic motivation

00:39:57.850 --> 00:40:03.050
for migration is to make a larger
argument about racial essentialism.

00:40:03.050 --> 00:40:06.000
It is to argue against
the notion that biological

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.370
and genetic signatures
confer innate,

00:40:09.370 --> 00:40:13.010
inescapable socio-behavioral
propensities

00:40:13.010 --> 00:40:17.160
that differentiate Africans from
Euro-Americans in a fundamental way

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:20.250
and make their migration
stories different.

00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:24.910
To be sure, my thesis is not a
disavowal of the obvious economic

00:40:24.910 --> 00:40:28.320
and existential stimuli
driving African migration

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:29.840
to the United States.

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:34.570 position:56%
Rather, I'm trying here to
synthesize the economic push factors

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:39.750
on the idea that migration is also
a quest for psychosocial relief.

00:40:39.750 --> 00:40:44.080
If we must account for the range of
motivations for African migration

00:40:44.080 --> 00:40:48.990 position:56%
to America in the 21st century, we
have to embrace an explanatory model

00:40:48.990 --> 00:40:52.760
that recognizes the obvious
economic motivations,

00:40:52.760 --> 00:40:55.620
as well as the increasingly
significant factor

00:40:55.620 --> 00:40:58.860
of convenient relocation.

00:40:58.860 --> 00:41:02.740 position:56%
One does not have to discount one
factor in order to stress the other.

00:41:02.740 --> 00:41:04.510
The psychosocial factors

00:41:04.510 --> 00:41:09.040
that influence some African
migratory decisions are not removed

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:13.650
from issues of poverty and
economic alienation either.

00:41:13.650 --> 00:41:16.690
In fact, I would argue that
there is a symbiotic relationship

00:41:16.690 --> 00:41:20.790
between the economy of suffering
and the psychosocial quest

00:41:20.790 --> 00:41:25.070
that I am trying to
enunciate in this paper.

00:41:25.070 --> 00:41:29.280
Psychosocial longings are sometimes
coextensive, I would argue,

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:33.570
with poverty, although, albeit
a different kind of poverty.

00:41:33.570 --> 00:41:37.450
And I'll talk about this
different kind of poverty shortly.

00:41:37.450 --> 00:41:38.750
It is obvious that poverty

00:41:38.750 --> 00:41:41.930
and economic destitution make
people want to move to places

00:41:41.930 --> 00:41:43.680
of perceived economic opportunity.

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:46.000
This is quite obvious.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.140
It doesn't have to be explained.

00:41:48.140 --> 00:41:50.030
But if we define poverty
and hardship,

00:41:50.030 --> 00:41:53.470
not only in starkly economic
terms but also in terms

00:41:53.470 --> 00:41:58.310
of what one may call the quality of
life poverty, then it is possible

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:01.790
to see how an economically
successful African professional

00:42:01.790 --> 00:42:06.800
in Africa could be poor in terms
of the quality of his or her life.

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:11.950
For analytical convenience,
let me call this kind

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:15.220
of poverty psychosocial poverty.

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:22.650 position:56%
OK? This kind of poverty is also an
impetus for migration out of Africa,

00:42:22.650 --> 00:42:26.560
for migration to America.

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:31.230
What I am positing here is what
one may call vicarious poverty,

00:42:31.230 --> 00:42:34.570
a situation in which
there will be migrant,

00:42:34.570 --> 00:42:38.730
migrant African does not experience
poverty directly but indirectly

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:42.890
through the trauma of living in
the midst of grinding poverty

00:42:42.890 --> 00:42:47.310
and of being assaulted daily by the
reminders and images of poverty,

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:51.780
economic collapse, infrastructural
deficits, and so forth.

00:42:51.780 --> 00:42:54.450
The psychological torture and
burden of such an environment

00:42:54.450 --> 00:43:01.010
of poverty can be as depressing
as actual personal poverty itself.

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:03.930
There are two aspects
to this phenomenon.

00:43:03.930 --> 00:43:06.540
The first one revolves
around the fact

00:43:06.540 --> 00:43:11.830 position:56%
that no matter how successful one is
in Africa, one still has to depend

00:43:11.830 --> 00:43:15.750 position:56%
to various degrees on state-provided
social services, among them;

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:19.140
electricity, water,
sewage, roads and security.

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:24.180
As we know or as we should
know, these services are poor

00:43:24.180 --> 00:43:26.120
in many African countries.

00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:29.750
So, one is forced to participate
in the broader experience

00:43:29.750 --> 00:43:32.210
of poverty and underdevelopment.

00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:36.250
One's economic success cannot
insulate one from this.

00:43:36.250 --> 00:43:40.330
Your quality of life will therefore
be poor and may motivate you

00:43:40.330 --> 00:43:44.000
to migrate to America or another
country in the Global North

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:47.060
where social services are
delivered more efficiently.

00:43:47.060 --> 00:43:51.150 position:56%
In other words, there is a limit to
the amount of comfort and material--

00:43:51.150 --> 00:43:55.660
that material success can
confer on you in Africa.

00:43:55.660 --> 00:44:00.050
The second aspect has to do with
the ironic psychosocial trauma

00:44:00.050 --> 00:44:01.950
of being successful in Africa.

00:44:01.950 --> 00:44:06.320 position:56%
In Africa, more so than in the West,

00:44:06.320 --> 00:44:10.310
the successful professional is
confronted daily by sights, sounds,

00:44:10.310 --> 00:44:13.340
and smells of acute poverty.

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:16.060
He is surrounded and
tortured by this poverty.

00:44:16.060 --> 00:44:19.680
He sees it in his employees or
colleagues, junior colleagues,

00:44:19.680 --> 00:44:24.500
neighbors, relatives, friends, and
coreligionists, as well as kinsmen.

00:44:24.500 --> 00:44:28.590
On his daily commute to work, his
sense of accomplishments is diluted

00:44:28.590 --> 00:44:32.080
and deflated by disturbing and
haunting images of destitution

00:44:32.080 --> 00:44:33.900
and economic hopelessness.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:38.460
These images nibble at his edifice
of-- at this edifice of success,

00:44:38.460 --> 00:44:41.750
filling him at once with
guilt and anxieties,

00:44:41.750 --> 00:44:45.440
and about what might have
been and what might still be.

00:44:45.440 --> 00:44:48.710
The images erode the
joys of economic success

00:44:48.710 --> 00:44:50.010
and make lofty economic

00:44:50.010 --> 00:44:55.060
and professional perches seem less
secure than they actually are.

00:44:55.060 --> 00:44:59.590
Insecurities, anxieties, guilt,
alienation, dissatisfaction,

00:44:59.590 --> 00:45:02.760
and depression take a toll
on the quality of one's life.

00:45:02.760 --> 00:45:06.790
I would argue that not a
few successful Africans,

00:45:06.790 --> 00:45:10.570
economically successful
Africans, have migrated to America

00:45:10.570 --> 00:45:13.220
to escape this quality
of life conundrum,

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:15.320
this unspoken existential turmoil

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:19.670
that hunts successful
professionals in Africa.

00:45:19.670 --> 00:45:24.860 position:56%
The paradox of being psychologically
miserable even while being

00:45:24.860 --> 00:45:28.680
materially successful allows the
African professional to migrate

00:45:28.680 --> 00:45:32.290
to America, not to escape
poverty, I would argue,

00:45:32.290 --> 00:45:35.110
or to survive economically
but to escape mentally

00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:38.490
and improve his quality of life in
the psychosocial sense of the word.

00:45:38.490 --> 00:45:42.880
What the migrant is escaping
is a kind of poverty,

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:45.210
a different kind of poverty.

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:48.820
Not the poverty portrayed by
CNN or National Geographic

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:52.510
or in Hollywood movies, right?

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:55.610
So, increasingly, we are talking

00:45:55.610 --> 00:46:00.870
about strategic migrants
and strategic migration.

00:46:00.870 --> 00:46:05.610
Many of today's African migrants to
America are most strategic migrants

00:46:05.610 --> 00:46:07.650
than they are economic
refugees, I would argue.

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:11.090
This is a not radical
statement to make actually

00:46:11.090 --> 00:46:14.290
since African migrants are
generally well-educated,

00:46:14.290 --> 00:46:17.740
even though the findings from
Professor Falola's work is--

00:46:17.740 --> 00:46:21.200
complicates that argument
a little bit.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:24.180
But generally, they
are very well-educated.

00:46:24.180 --> 00:46:27.140
There are arguments that they
are also self-selected, right?

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:29.880
And strategically mobile,
people who are chosen

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:31.860
to be strategically mobile.

00:46:31.860 --> 00:46:34.870
Whether they are beneficiaries
of the US Visa Lottery program

00:46:34.870 --> 00:46:39.230
or students who came here to study,
like myself, or professionals

00:46:39.230 --> 00:46:42.830
who came here to take up positions
in US firms and institutions,

00:46:42.830 --> 00:46:47.120
many African migrants to the United
States increasingly do not fit

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:51.670
into the refugee-- the
refuge and exile paradigm.

00:46:51.670 --> 00:46:55.850
Instead, they are a
pre-selected, relatively privileged

00:46:55.850 --> 00:46:59.440
and prepared collection of
people who, for the most part,

00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:02.090
were already set apart
to varying degrees

00:47:02.090 --> 00:47:06.120
in their home countries prior
to their migration to America.

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:08.040
There are people who
are not representative

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:11.290
of the general populations
of their countries.

00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:16.060
Their migrant itineraries and
biographies undermine the concept

00:47:16.060 --> 00:47:21.150 position:56%
which so many of you have heard, the
concept of model minority, right?

00:47:21.150 --> 00:47:25.930 position:56%
This prior preparation and privilege
rarely makes it into the scholarly

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:30.300
and popular discussions of
African migration to America.

00:47:30.300 --> 00:47:34.150
Studies on African migration to the
United States rarely acknowledge,

00:47:34.150 --> 00:47:37.200
let alone illuminate
this growing phenomenon

00:47:37.200 --> 00:47:41.460
of psychosocial strategic migrants.

00:47:41.460 --> 00:47:44.730
This phenomenon has grown
and will continue to account

00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:46.860
for more African migration
to America

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:50.380
in the coming years given
the continued growth

00:47:50.380 --> 00:47:54.170
of the African middle class in
the midst of expanding populations

00:47:54.170 --> 00:47:58.770
of poor people on crumbling
infrastructure.

00:47:58.770 --> 00:48:03.250
This dynamic of middle class
expansion, deepening poverty

00:48:03.250 --> 00:48:06.570
and deteriorating infrastructure,
I would argue,

00:48:06.570 --> 00:48:08.400
is key to understanding the rise

00:48:08.400 --> 00:48:11.690
of strategic African
migration to America.

00:48:11.690 --> 00:48:16.390
This migratory flow caused
by psychosocial alienation

00:48:16.390 --> 00:48:20.240
and yearning for-- yearning, as
well as a systemic-- systematic--

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:24.270 position:56%
systemic poverty and infrastructural
collapse, is likely to continue

00:48:24.270 --> 00:48:29.020
as corporations and institutions in
the United States aggressively seek

00:48:29.020 --> 00:48:33.300
out talent without regard to the
north-south dichotomies of old.

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:40.700
We already see that African
professionals in multiple fields,

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:43.920
some of them with experience
in multinational corporations

00:48:43.920 --> 00:48:45.650
on the African side are take--

00:48:45.650 --> 00:48:48.410
increasingly taking
positions in the global note

00:48:48.410 --> 00:48:49.730
and relocating with their families.

00:48:49.730 --> 00:48:53.350
I have-- actually I have friends
who used to work in these--

00:48:53.350 --> 00:48:55.610
some of these multinational
companies back home who have--

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:59.070
who are doing very well, much
better than I am doing in America

00:48:59.070 --> 00:49:03.400 position:56%
but who nonetheless chose to migrate
with their families to America.

00:49:03.400 --> 00:49:06.060
This is happening increasingly.

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:09.640
So, my argument is then that
we need a new vocabulary,

00:49:09.640 --> 00:49:14.320
a new conceptual idiom to
explain the migratory choices

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:17.680
of these new African
migrants and to tell--

00:49:17.680 --> 00:49:21.930 position:56%
to be able to tell their stories
alongside the other stories as well.

00:49:21.930 --> 00:49:25.940
In the African immigrant's
journey to--

00:49:25.940 --> 00:49:30.780
If the African immigrant's journey
to America is a manifestation

00:49:30.780 --> 00:49:37.690
of his efforts to make--
to take control of his life

00:49:37.690 --> 00:49:41.530 position:56%
and destiny while escaping the
conditions that diminish the quality

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:43.670 position:56%
of his life in Africa, the processes

00:49:43.670 --> 00:49:46.700
that make the journey
possible are shaped by forces

00:49:46.700 --> 00:49:50.130
and narratives beyond his
or her control in America.

00:49:50.130 --> 00:49:55.260
The African-- beyond his
or her control in America.

00:49:55.260 --> 00:49:58.760
But these forces are also
available to him to manipulate.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:02.050
Furthermore, once he
is situated in America,

00:50:02.050 --> 00:50:06.040
the African immigrant's life and
choices are no longer his own.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:08.670
Rather, they are shaped
by the circumstances

00:50:08.670 --> 00:50:12.660
and ideological positions
produced by the political dynamics

00:50:12.660 --> 00:50:15.720 position:56%
and the politics of
self-fashioning in American society.

00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:17.900
Both the migratory process

00:50:17.900 --> 00:50:23.040
and the way the migrant narrates
his experience are then constrained

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:27.150
and reshaped by preexisting
discursive regimes in America,

00:50:27.150 --> 00:50:30.450
which perhaps explains why
in spite of the increase

00:50:30.450 --> 00:50:34.250
in professional migrations,
strategic migrations from Africa,

00:50:34.250 --> 00:50:37.470
the migration as economic
escape paradigm continues

00:50:37.470 --> 00:50:39.850
to dominate perspective
and discussions

00:50:39.850 --> 00:50:42.660
on African migration
to the United States.

00:50:42.660 --> 00:50:46.590
This dissonance between the
complexity of the African story

00:50:46.590 --> 00:50:50.920
of migration to America and its
simplistic reduction to story

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:54.410
of suffering and rescue
should be explained.

00:50:54.410 --> 00:50:59.470
So, I return now to
my earlier question.

00:50:59.470 --> 00:51:04.480
Why is the economic refugee
exile paradigm so persistent?

00:51:04.480 --> 00:51:08.500
Why does it seem to overshadow
the increasing phenomenon

00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:12.010
of African strategic
migration to the United States?

00:51:12.010 --> 00:51:15.230
I want to conclude by offering
a few tentative answers

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:17.270
to these questions.

00:51:17.270 --> 00:51:21.950
The paternalistic racial attitude
of Western Liberals construct

00:51:21.950 --> 00:51:26.020
and legitimize certain migratory
stereotypes, I would argue.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:31.110
It also privileges and silences
certain migratory narratives

00:51:31.110 --> 00:51:36.460 position:56%
and cause African migrants to become
active participants in this process

00:51:36.460 --> 00:51:39.160
of silencing in a myth-making.

00:51:39.160 --> 00:51:43.270 position:56%
Liberal America's appetite for
dramatic African immigration stories

00:51:43.270 --> 00:51:49.150
of escape, heroic, self-redemption
and exile confers validity

00:51:49.150 --> 00:51:54.400
on immigrant narratives that
confirm these same stereotypes.

00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:59.430
These stories reaffirm America's
fate in the foundational reputation

00:51:59.430 --> 00:52:05.230
of their country as a land of
refuge and compassionate to rescue,

00:52:05.230 --> 00:52:09.340
and of Africa as a land
of poverty and misery.

00:52:09.340 --> 00:52:13.040
Other narratives of migration
and other migratory experiences

00:52:13.040 --> 00:52:16.440
and trajectories are marginalized
when stories of poverty

00:52:16.440 --> 00:52:19.960
and suffering-induced
migration are privileged.

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:24.330
The refugee is also a trope of
the conservative American view

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:26.760
of African migration to America.

00:52:26.760 --> 00:52:29.850
And migrant stories and realities
that depart from the figure

00:52:29.850 --> 00:52:35.320 position:56%
of the refugee are unintelligible to
American conservative sensibilities.

00:52:35.320 --> 00:52:38.350
Americans of the conservative
bend buy into the narrative

00:52:38.350 --> 00:52:43.660
of African economic dysfunction and
therefore imagine Africans largely

00:52:43.660 --> 00:52:47.460
as objects of American
humanitarian intervention.

00:52:47.460 --> 00:52:49.550
This means that they
cannot imagine Africans

00:52:49.550 --> 00:52:52.790
that are economically
successful in their homelands.

00:52:52.790 --> 00:52:57.840
