In fact, in 1899, Bishop
Henry McNeal Turner

01:07:51.660 --> 01:07:55.140
of the African Methodist
Episcopal Zion Church noted,

01:07:55.140 --> 01:07:59.380
"Everybody appears to be amazed
at their learning refinement

01:07:59.380 --> 01:08:01.410
and general intelligence.

01:08:01.410 --> 01:08:02.710
So many of our people

01:08:02.710 --> 01:08:05.440
in this country believe all
Africans are mere heathens,

01:08:05.440 --> 01:08:10.240
that they are paralyzed with
surprise to find such boys coming."

01:08:10.240 --> 01:08:13.780
And I'm sorry the slide I left
out is on the next section.

01:08:13.780 --> 01:08:17.210
James Aggrey was perhaps the
most famous African to arrive

01:08:17.210 --> 01:08:21.210
in the United States in that
era, and might well be deemed one

01:08:21.210 --> 01:08:24.270
of the first African
immigrants in the United States,

01:08:24.270 --> 01:08:26.310
although he isn't often
thought of as such.

01:08:26.310 --> 01:08:28.010
Now, I grew up listening to stories

01:08:28.010 --> 01:08:30.260
about James Aggrey
at the dinner table.

01:08:30.260 --> 01:08:32.800
My father hero worships
James Aggrey.

01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:36.050
But in anything that he said
or in anything that I ever read

01:08:36.050 --> 01:08:40.200
about James Aggrey, he's never
mentioned as an African immigrant

01:08:40.200 --> 01:08:44.480
in the United States and
I construct him as such.

01:08:44.480 --> 01:08:48.070
Born in the Gold Coast, later
Ghana, Aggrey attended mission

01:08:48.070 --> 01:08:51.890
and colonial schools in the British
colony excelling in his studies.

01:08:51.890 --> 01:08:55.960 position:56%
He soon came to the notice of
missionaries and colonial officials.

01:08:55.960 --> 01:08:57.920
And in 1898, he was sponsored

01:08:57.920 --> 01:09:01.340
by Bishop Bryan Small
of the AME Zion Church.

01:09:01.340 --> 01:09:05.530
And he came to-- was brought by
Bishop Small to the United States

01:09:05.530 --> 01:09:10.700
in 1898 to study at Livingston
College in North Carolina.

01:09:10.700 --> 01:09:13.890
Aggrey completed his studies at
Livingston, later becoming a member

01:09:13.890 --> 01:09:16.790
of faculty and an administrator.

01:09:16.790 --> 01:09:19.100
He remained in the United
States until his death

01:09:19.100 --> 01:09:24.400 position:56%
in 1927 marrying Rose Douglas, an
African-American woman from Virginia

01:09:24.400 --> 01:09:28.140
and raising his family
in North Carolina.

01:09:28.140 --> 01:09:31.900
Although he continued to highlight
his African heritage expressing his

01:09:31.900 --> 01:09:35.210
love and devotion to his
homeland, he dedicated himself

01:09:35.210 --> 01:09:38.230
to the improvement and
uplift of African-Americans.

01:09:38.230 --> 01:09:41.350
He was popular with students
and had a great reputation,

01:09:41.350 --> 01:09:45.130
a classmate of his noted.

01:09:45.130 --> 01:09:50.010 position:56%
WJ Trent, this classmate also
observed that Aggrey's influence was

01:09:50.010 --> 01:09:53.060
"very precious and had a great
deal to do with the improvement

01:09:53.060 --> 01:09:55.510
of the moral and spiritual
conditions

01:09:55.510 --> 01:09:57.830
of the whole college life."

01:09:57.830 --> 01:10:01.080
Having been ordained in the AME
Zion Church, Aggrey preached

01:10:01.080 --> 01:10:03.600
in black churches all
over North Carolina.

01:10:03.600 --> 01:10:05.720
He pastored two African
American churches

01:10:05.720 --> 01:10:09.210
in rural communities
in that state as well.

01:10:09.210 --> 01:10:12.660
His parishioners were mostly
poor, illiterate, rural people,

01:10:12.660 --> 01:10:14.860
mainly farmers and laborers.

01:10:14.860 --> 01:10:18.180
Working with these communities was
one of the most fulfilling aspects

01:10:18.180 --> 01:10:20.740
of Aggrey's work in
the United States.

01:10:20.740 --> 01:10:25.180
His biographer tells us, "it took
him out of an academic atmosphere

01:10:25.180 --> 01:10:27.210
and introduced him
to the actualities

01:10:27.210 --> 01:10:30.140
of life led by the American Negro."

01:10:30.140 --> 01:10:33.800
Clearly, his relationship with
African-Americans was characterized

01:10:33.800 --> 01:10:37.590
by mutual respect as is evident
from the many outpourings of grief

01:10:37.590 --> 01:10:40.240
from African-Americans
after his death.

01:10:40.240 --> 01:10:43.980
The bibliophile Arthur
Schomburg, in remembering Aggrey,

01:10:43.980 --> 01:10:47.390
pointed out his influence and
legacy in the United States,

01:10:47.390 --> 01:10:51.140
describing his contributions
to black Americans.

01:10:51.140 --> 01:10:54.600
"At a Native American
school, Livingston College,

01:10:54.600 --> 01:10:57.980
set in the panoramic mountains
of Salisbury, North Carolina,"

01:10:57.980 --> 01:11:00.950
Schomburg said, "he
received the milk of kindness

01:11:00.950 --> 01:11:03.240
and remained with his own people.

01:11:03.240 --> 01:11:06.540
Later his loved joined
that of an American Rose

01:11:06.540 --> 01:11:09.990
and made his stay permanent
among us."

01:11:09.990 --> 01:11:12.570 position:56%
Yet Aggrey also felt his difference.

01:11:12.570 --> 01:11:14.920
And there are signs that
he was not fully accepted

01:11:14.920 --> 01:11:17.280
as an American despite
his citizenship

01:11:17.280 --> 01:11:19.940 position:56%
and Aggrey actually was naturalized.

01:11:19.940 --> 01:11:23.290 position:56%
He felt the strain of being excluded
from the larger white society,

01:11:23.290 --> 01:11:27.070
but he also felt slighted
by African-Americans.

01:11:27.070 --> 01:11:31.040
His biographer writes that Aggrey
was accepted by whites more easily

01:11:31.040 --> 01:11:34.550
than native-born blacks, making
it harder for him to get along

01:11:34.550 --> 01:11:36.940
with some African-Americans.

01:11:36.940 --> 01:11:40.580
He gained the respect and ardent
affection of a number of these

01:11:40.580 --> 01:11:44.780
but in the minds of not a few,
the old prejudice persisted.

01:11:44.780 --> 01:11:47.640
In 1917, Aggrey was
up for the position

01:11:47.640 --> 01:11:50.190
of president of Livingston College.

01:11:50.190 --> 01:11:52.860
He was not offered the
position and believed it was

01:11:52.860 --> 01:11:56.820
because he was not a
native-born black American.

01:11:56.820 --> 01:11:59.080
Though he later was
offered the position,

01:11:59.080 --> 01:12:01.410
he declined it at that time.

01:12:01.410 --> 01:12:03.660
He appears to have been
passed up for other positions

01:12:03.660 --> 01:12:07.790
which he attributed to his foreign
status rather than his race.

01:12:07.790 --> 01:12:11.270
In a letter to his wife
he wrote, "I am convinced

01:12:11.270 --> 01:12:14.300
that being a foreigner," and
he puts foreigner in quotes,

01:12:14.300 --> 01:12:18.350
"I could never command in any sort
of place the decent kind of a job

01:12:18.350 --> 01:12:21.460
in this country that would
keep me to take care of you

01:12:21.460 --> 01:12:24.710
and give the children the
education they deserve.

01:12:24.710 --> 01:12:26.210
That is the way I see it.

01:12:26.210 --> 01:12:27.790
You may not see it that way.

01:12:27.790 --> 01:12:30.310
I am resigned to my fate."

01:12:30.310 --> 01:12:33.560
He went on to tell Rose of
another African, one Norman Wilson

01:12:33.560 --> 01:12:37.520
from Sierra Leone, living in
New York who faced the same sort

01:12:37.520 --> 01:12:41.180
of discrimination, "Thwarted
at every turn in his desire

01:12:41.180 --> 01:12:43.290
for advancement," Aggrey noted,

01:12:43.290 --> 01:12:46.040
"that Wilson was considering
a return to Africa

01:12:46.040 --> 01:12:50.160
because he tells me his brother
priest have been fighting him

01:12:50.160 --> 01:12:52.000
because he's a foreigner.

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:53.930
He has had to go to the bishop.

01:12:53.930 --> 01:12:56.150
He says he's getting tired of it.

01:12:56.150 --> 01:12:59.230
They acknowledged his work and
his influence but they fight him

01:12:59.230 --> 01:13:02.180
in an underhand way
because he is a foreigner.

01:13:02.180 --> 01:13:05.030
Too bad for our race, too bad.

01:13:05.030 --> 01:13:07.420
He has finished his
work for his BA degree.

01:13:07.420 --> 01:13:11.030
He tells me he hopes this will
be his last year at this working

01:13:11.030 --> 01:13:15.770
under such stress, the
everlasting foreigner nag."

01:13:15.770 --> 01:13:18.800
No doubt their foreign
status was significant.

01:13:18.800 --> 01:13:22.870
But in the 1920s when Aggrey
wrote their race was surely just

01:13:22.870 --> 01:13:26.490
as important to their
inability to advance.

01:13:26.490 --> 01:13:28.200
Like Aggrey-- And I
do have the slide

01:13:28.200 --> 01:13:36.390
for this, if I can get back to it.

01:13:36.390 --> 01:13:40.810 position:56%
Like Aggrey, Orishatukeh Faduma came
to the United States as a student

01:13:40.810 --> 01:13:44.190
and stayed becoming an immigrant.

01:13:44.190 --> 01:13:48.240
Born William Davis in Sierra Leone,
Faduma came to the United States

01:13:48.240 --> 01:13:54.880
in 1890-- sorry, a slide one back.

01:13:57.030 --> 01:13:59.470
Here we go, sorry.

01:13:59.470 --> 01:14:02.970
OK, I should stop touching it.

01:14:02.970 --> 01:14:09.330
Faduma came to the United States
in 1890 to study at Yale--

01:14:09.330 --> 01:14:11.420
It's doing it on its own.

01:14:11.420 --> 01:14:13.410
Am I pressing it too hard?

01:14:13.410 --> 01:14:16.510
It's not that important.

01:14:16.510 --> 01:14:17.810
OK.

01:14:17.810 --> 01:14:19.320
&gt;&gt; Toyin Falola: Very sensitive.

01:14:19.320 --> 01:14:20.720
&gt;&gt; Nemata Blyden: Is it looping?

01:14:20.720 --> 01:14:23.100
He came to study at the
Yale Divinity School

01:14:23.100 --> 01:14:24.400
in New Haven, Connecticut.

01:14:24.400 --> 01:14:27.910 position:56%
After completing his degree in 1894,

01:14:27.910 --> 01:14:30.140
he took a position in
the American South.

01:14:30.140 --> 01:14:33.630
Like Aggrey, he married an
African-American woman Henrietta

01:14:33.630 --> 01:14:37.190
Adams from Georgia, and
taught at the Peabody Academy,

01:14:37.190 --> 01:14:41.630
a black institution in Troy,
North Carolina for 17 years.

01:14:41.630 --> 01:14:44.300
Served as a missionary and
educator to African-Americans

01:14:44.300 --> 01:14:49.190
in North Carolina for 50
years until he died in 1946.

01:14:49.190 --> 01:14:51.800
In 1913, Faduma worked closely

01:14:51.800 --> 01:14:54.410
with the African-American
Chief Alfred Sam and his Back

01:14:54.410 --> 01:14:58.940 position:56%
to Africa movement, encouraging
black Americans to return to Africa.

01:14:58.940 --> 01:15:03.780
Though he himself never returned
becoming naturalized in 1902,

01:15:03.780 --> 01:15:05.330
he spent the rest of his life

01:15:05.330 --> 01:15:09.210
in the United States living
among African-Americans.

01:15:09.210 --> 01:15:12.560
Both Faduma and Aggrey, like
many Africans in that era,

01:15:12.560 --> 01:15:16.510
lived in a segregated south and
operated within a world in which

01:15:16.510 --> 01:15:18.620
by virtue of the color
of their skin,

01:15:18.620 --> 01:15:20.860
they were thought to be inferior.

01:15:20.860 --> 01:15:23.240
Both men adapted to
their lives as black men

01:15:23.240 --> 01:15:26.980
in a racially segregated nation,
at a time when discrimination

01:15:26.980 --> 01:15:31.200
and racism were leveled at men
and women of African descent.

01:15:31.200 --> 01:15:34.760
Both lived and worked among the
less privileged African-Americans

01:15:34.760 --> 01:15:38.530
and saw it as their responsibility
and duty to enhance their lives

01:15:38.530 --> 01:15:43.170
and improve their condition, which
was kind of a reverse, right,

01:15:43.170 --> 01:15:44.470
with Faduma referring

01:15:44.470 --> 01:15:47.700
to African-Americans
as his kith and kin.

01:15:47.700 --> 01:15:51.820
His contributions were
recognized in the 1904 publication.

01:15:51.820 --> 01:15:55.690
In an article profiling him, he
was lauded for his contributions

01:15:55.690 --> 01:15:59.580
to African-Americans and for
his missionary work among them.

01:15:59.580 --> 01:16:01.980
The article noted, "We question

01:16:01.980 --> 01:16:05.280
if this Native African could
have made a better investment

01:16:05.280 --> 01:16:08.940
of his powers had he
remained in Africa.

01:16:08.940 --> 01:16:10.990
Africa is here."

01:16:10.990 --> 01:16:14.710
Although Aggrey and Faduma settled
in the south, a few Africans lived

01:16:14.710 --> 01:16:16.980
in northern cities like New York.

01:16:16.980 --> 01:16:20.350
And over the years, blacks from
Africa continued to migrate

01:16:20.350 --> 01:16:23.100
to the United States
for various reasons.

01:16:23.100 --> 01:16:24.400
While relations

01:16:24.400 --> 01:16:26.350
with African-Americans
were not always positive,

01:16:26.350 --> 01:16:30.260 position:56%
Africans found more
commonalities with African-Americans

01:16:30.260 --> 01:16:32.410
than with the larger white society.

01:16:32.410 --> 01:16:34.160
For the most part in
these early years,

01:16:34.160 --> 01:16:37.440
Africans faced the same
discrimination from white Americans

01:16:37.440 --> 01:16:39.740
as their native-born counterparts.

01:16:39.740 --> 01:16:42.560
Although some highlighted their
difference and distinctiveness

01:16:42.560 --> 01:16:46.260
from black Americans, what white
Americans often saw was their

01:16:46.260 --> 01:16:47.630
black skin.

01:16:47.630 --> 01:16:52.180 position:56%
On the other hand, African-Americans
frequently welcome them as brethren.

01:16:52.180 --> 01:16:57.280
In a 1971 interview, Bishop William
Jacob Walls, an African alumnus

01:16:57.280 --> 01:17:01.050
of Livingston College where
Aggrey had attended remembered

01:17:01.050 --> 01:17:05.900
that Africans were not looked down
upon us inferior by this campus.

01:17:05.900 --> 01:17:11.000 position:56%
For many Africans, the issues facing
African-Americans came to be theirs.

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:13.280
In the period before the 1960s,

01:17:13.280 --> 01:17:15.950
perhaps because their
numbers were small and because

01:17:15.950 --> 01:17:18.810
of the hostile environment in
which they often found themselves,

01:17:18.810 --> 01:17:22.400
Africans living in the
United States lived alongside

01:17:22.400 --> 01:17:24.500
and among black Americans.

01:17:24.500 --> 01:17:26.980
Although they may have held
particular views and stereotypes

01:17:26.980 --> 01:17:30.930
of African-Americans-- of Africans
before arriving as they lived

01:17:30.930 --> 01:17:33.400
in the United States
for extended periods,

01:17:33.400 --> 01:17:37.050
they relied on African-Americans
for an understanding of the society

01:17:37.050 --> 01:17:38.980
into which they had come.

01:17:38.980 --> 01:17:43.430
The 1965 Hart-Celler Immigration
Bill would change the size,

01:17:43.430 --> 01:17:45.830
composition and demographic profile

01:17:45.830 --> 01:17:48.800
of the African population
in the United States.

01:17:48.800 --> 01:17:52.240
This act, liberalizing
American immigration laws,

01:17:52.240 --> 01:17:55.640
would change to some extent too
the nature of the relationship

01:17:55.640 --> 01:17:58.230
between African-Americans
and Africans.

01:17:58.230 --> 01:18:01.630
Coming at the height of the Civil
Rights Movement, Africans studying

01:18:01.630 --> 01:18:04.220
in American colleges often
found themselves in the midst

01:18:04.220 --> 01:18:07.930
of agitation, civil rights
protests and marches, sit-ins

01:18:07.930 --> 01:18:10.370
and other attempts
by African-Americans

01:18:10.370 --> 01:18:13.530
to desegregate public
spaces and institutions.

01:18:13.530 --> 01:18:16.460
Africans sometimes were
mistaken for black Americans

01:18:16.460 --> 01:18:18.750
and face the same racial profiling.

01:18:18.750 --> 01:18:23.230
As the United States increasingly
became a desegregated society

01:18:23.230 --> 01:18:26.970
and one that was more open to
foreigners, Africans continue

01:18:26.970 --> 01:18:31.130
to arrive on its shores in larger
numbers now finding themselves

01:18:31.130 --> 01:18:34.400 position:56%
with more options and opportunities.

01:18:34.400 --> 01:18:38.190
Coming from newly African-- newly
independent African nations,

01:18:38.190 --> 01:18:42.000
many saw a little need to
settle among black Americans.

01:18:42.000 --> 01:18:45.030
As the number and composition
of African immigrants has grown,

01:18:45.030 --> 01:18:48.150
so have the perceptions that
they, like other immigrants,

01:18:48.150 --> 01:18:50.720
are different from
African-Americans.

01:18:50.720 --> 01:18:54.260 position:56%
While during the era of segregation,
black immigrants were often forced

01:18:54.260 --> 01:18:57.250
to live alongside black
Americans, the new liberal

01:18:57.250 --> 01:19:01.300 position:56%
and relatively tolerable post-civil
rights America has given more recent

01:19:01.300 --> 01:19:05.330
immigrants the opportunity to live
apart from and distance themselves

01:19:05.330 --> 01:19:07.630
from African-American populations.

01:19:07.630 --> 01:19:10.000
These black immigrants
are no longer settling

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:13.410
in traditional gateway cities
like New York or Miami but more

01:19:13.410 --> 01:19:16.680
and more attracted to suburban
areas or as in the case

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:19.920
of Somalis in Maine to rural areas.

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:22.120
Despite the racial stereotypes,

01:19:22.120 --> 01:19:24.590
some black immigrants
prefer settling among mixed

01:19:24.590 --> 01:19:27.920
or largely white populations
believing that assimilating

01:19:27.920 --> 01:19:32.680
with African-Americans would hinder
their socioeconomic advancement.

01:19:32.680 --> 01:19:36.350
African immigrants also fear
the loss of ethnic identity

01:19:36.350 --> 01:19:38.860
and they highlight their
distinctive heritage.

01:19:38.860 --> 01:19:41.770
As immigrants, they have sometimes
lacked an understanding of

01:19:41.770 --> 01:19:43.600
and do not identify

01:19:43.600 --> 01:19:47.850
with post-slavery issues affecting
native-born American blacks.

01:19:47.850 --> 01:19:50.840
As one young African
immigrant interviewed

01:19:50.840 --> 01:19:53.340
for an Arizona news article stated,

01:19:53.340 --> 01:19:56.260
"I don't associate
myself with slavery."

01:19:56.260 --> 01:20:00.080
The article notes that these
new African-Americans lack ties

01:20:00.080 --> 01:20:04.230
to American slavery and the inner
city culture frequently associated

01:20:04.230 --> 01:20:05.810
with black America.

01:20:05.810 --> 01:20:09.650
Many grew up in middle-class,
two-parent families and have access

01:20:09.650 --> 01:20:13.100
to social networks that include
doctors, nurses, engineers,

01:20:13.100 --> 01:20:15.970
professors and business executive.

01:20:15.970 --> 01:20:19.300
Nonetheless, urban areas
remain important destinations

01:20:19.300 --> 01:20:22.350
for some African immigrants
who choose or are forced

01:20:22.350 --> 01:20:25.610
by economic circumstances
to settle in areas

01:20:25.610 --> 01:20:28.580
with significant black
American populations.

01:20:28.580 --> 01:20:31.800
These immigrants recognize
their status as a minority

01:20:31.800 --> 01:20:34.060
and understand the
consequences of ethnicity

01:20:34.060 --> 01:20:36.260
and race in the United States.

01:20:36.260 --> 01:20:39.330
African immigrants increasingly
recognize the struggles

01:20:39.330 --> 01:20:43.180
of African-Americans in providing
the world into which they came.

01:20:43.180 --> 01:20:46.920
One immigrant remarked, "We feel
that those African-Americans

01:20:46.920 --> 01:20:49.400
who were here before
were the pioneers.

01:20:49.400 --> 01:20:53.170
If it wasn't for Martin Luther King
Jr. and the Civil Rights Movement,

01:20:53.170 --> 01:20:55.640
we wouldn't be here
in the first place."

01:20:55.640 --> 01:20:58.470
And as one scholar has
noted, black migrants,

01:20:58.470 --> 01:21:02.380
unlike light-skinned migrants,
also face an entirely different set

01:21:02.380 --> 01:21:06.850
of issues directly related to
fitting in with American society.

01:21:06.850 --> 01:21:10.290
They must reconstruct and
redefine their identity in terms

01:21:10.290 --> 01:21:15.240
of the American society's system
of race relations and hierarchy.

01:21:15.240 --> 01:21:18.180
This, they sometimes
find difficult to do.

01:21:18.180 --> 01:21:22.130 position:56%
As one immigrant noted, African
immigrants sometimes struggle to fit

01:21:22.130 --> 01:21:24.710
into black American
culture that has been shaped

01:21:24.710 --> 01:21:27.470
by civil disobedience
and peaceful protest.

01:21:27.470 --> 01:21:32.000 position:56%
Many hesitate to speak out on race
issues because they fear deportation

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:34.960
or showing disrespect to
their adopted homeland.

01:21:34.960 --> 01:21:36.950
They have, largely, not
integrated themselves

01:21:36.950 --> 01:21:38.650
into African-American institutions

01:21:38.650 --> 01:21:41.750
and organizations often
creating separate ethnic,

01:21:41.750 --> 01:21:44.970
hometown or country associations.

01:21:44.970 --> 01:21:46.930
This reluctance to identify fully

01:21:46.930 --> 01:21:49.240
with the African-Americans
has sometimes led

01:21:49.240 --> 01:21:51.650
to tensions between the two groups.

01:21:51.650 --> 01:21:53.820
For example, at the turn
of the 21st century,

01:21:53.820 --> 01:21:57.800
several incidents highlighted the
differences between the two groups.

01:21:57.800 --> 01:22:02.870
In 2005, an Ivorian street vendor
in Harlem frequently harassed

01:22:02.870 --> 01:22:08.280 position:56%
by black Americans lashed out in
return, resulting in a street brawl.

01:22:08.280 --> 01:22:11.830
While these incidents are
infrequent, they nevertheless point

01:22:11.830 --> 01:22:13.540
at continued misunderstandings

01:22:13.540 --> 01:22:16.540
between African-Americans
and black immigrants.

01:22:16.540 --> 01:22:19.660
Stereotypical views and
representations of Africa continue

01:22:19.660 --> 01:22:21.340
to be shown in mainstream media.

01:22:21.340 --> 01:22:23.410
Negative images and ideas

01:22:23.410 --> 01:22:26.880
about Africa still persist
among African-Americans,

01:22:26.880 --> 01:22:29.900
largely because African Americans
students still are not taught much

01:22:29.900 --> 01:22:33.090
about Africa, and when
exposed to Africans fall back

01:22:33.090 --> 01:22:36.720
on old stereotypes of Africa
as the "Dark Continent".

01:22:36.720 --> 01:22:39.010
Also at the heart of
African-American suspicion

01:22:39.010 --> 01:22:42.330
of black immigrants is the belief
that they are competing for jobs

01:22:42.330 --> 01:22:45.240
and other opportunities
and resources with them.

01:22:45.240 --> 01:22:49.120
As the scholar John Bracey
observed of the Harlem incident,

01:22:49.120 --> 01:22:52.390
Africans are seen as
another immigrant group

01:22:52.390 --> 01:22:55.340
that is pushing past
African-Americans.

01:22:55.340 --> 01:22:57.470
This is particular issue
of black immigrants

01:22:57.470 --> 01:23:01.200
who some African Americans believe
are given preference for employment

01:23:01.200 --> 01:23:03.970
by white employees-- employers.

01:23:03.970 --> 01:23:08.620
Louis Chude-Sokei points out that
"whites have historically tended

01:23:08.620 --> 01:23:11.530
to regard black immigrants
as a model minority

01:23:11.530 --> 01:23:14.970
within a troublesome
native-born black population.

01:23:14.970 --> 01:23:17.660
A good proportion of immigrants,
tend to be better educated

01:23:17.660 --> 01:23:21.390
than African-Americans, don't
have the chip or racial resentment

01:23:21.390 --> 01:23:24.930
on their shoulder and exhibit
the classic immigrant optimism

01:23:24.930 --> 01:23:28.940
about assimilation into the
mainstream culture," he argues.

01:23:28.940 --> 01:23:30.560
On the other hand, misconceptions

01:23:30.560 --> 01:23:34.040
about African-Americans
persist among Africans as well.

01:23:34.040 --> 01:23:37.590
The belief perpetuated by
the media and other sources

01:23:37.590 --> 01:23:40.920
that African-Americans are not hard
working and frequently fall back

01:23:40.920 --> 01:23:42.520
on the history of racism

01:23:42.520 --> 01:23:46.560
to make excuses still
persists among some Africans.

01:23:46.560 --> 01:23:50.490
As Bill Fletcher, president of
TransAfrica Forum commented,

01:23:50.490 --> 01:23:52.580
"Many African-Americans
are embarrassed

01:23:52.580 --> 01:23:53.960
or ambivalent about Africa.

01:23:53.960 --> 01:23:56.620
And many Africans have
misconceptions

01:23:56.620 --> 01:24:00.040
about the opportunities
available to African-Americans.

01:24:00.040 --> 01:24:03.100
They often fail to appreciate
what the African-Americans have

01:24:03.100 --> 01:24:04.970
gone through."

01:24:04.970 --> 01:24:08.520
African immigrant attempts to
maintain a distinct identity

01:24:08.520 --> 01:24:11.100
from African-Americans,
allows them the hope

01:24:11.100 --> 01:24:16.180
of protecting their children from
racialization in American society.

01:24:16.180 --> 01:24:19.420
Nonetheless, while African
immigrants in their attempt to cope

01:24:19.420 --> 01:24:20.720
with the racial hierarchy

01:24:20.720 --> 01:24:24.100 position:56%
in the United States have
frequently claimed a foreign status,

01:24:24.100 --> 01:24:27.920
they find it hard to insulate
themselves from white--

01:24:27.920 --> 01:24:30.650
racial stereotypes
and discrimination.

01:24:30.650 --> 01:24:33.580
Africans settling in urban
areas are more likely to closer

01:24:33.580 --> 01:24:36.620
to the African-Americans
resulting in some tensions

01:24:36.620 --> 01:24:39.200
but also providing the
opportunity for the group to learn

01:24:39.200 --> 01:24:42.720
about each other and in some
instances to work together

01:24:42.720 --> 01:24:47.060
in both social and political
causes and on an individual level.

01:24:47.060 --> 01:24:51.230
Though misunderstanding persists,
in recent years, as in past years,

01:24:51.230 --> 01:24:53.720
these groups have cooperated
with each other rather

01:24:53.720 --> 01:24:56.350 position:56%
than highlighting their differences.

01:24:56.350 --> 01:25:00.800
And in most major metropolitan
areas and even in smaller suburbs,

01:25:00.800 --> 01:25:04.320
African businesses and
organizations can now be found

01:25:04.320 --> 01:25:06.530
as established institutions.

01:25:06.530 --> 01:25:10.150 position:56%
Whether they're hair braiding salons
or Senegalese restaurants in Harlem,

01:25:10.150 --> 01:25:14.220
or the many African grocery
stores in Woodbridge, Virginia,

01:25:14.220 --> 01:25:17.740
these businesses have become a
familiar part of the landscape.

01:25:17.740 --> 01:25:20.270
They are patronized not
only by other Africans

01:25:20.270 --> 01:25:22.630
but also African-Americans.

01:25:22.630 --> 01:25:25.540
Likewise, the many African
churches springing up in cities

01:25:25.540 --> 01:25:28.370
and suburbs all over the
country are drawing African

01:25:28.370 --> 01:25:29.950
American congregants.

01:25:29.950 --> 01:25:32.970
In other words, the relationship
between black immigrants

01:25:32.970 --> 01:25:37.290
and American-born blacks is not
always characterized by tension.

01:25:37.290 --> 01:25:41.070
Like Aggrey and Faduma, black
immigrants are also intermarrying

01:25:41.070 --> 01:25:43.500
in greater numbers with
the African-Americans.

01:25:43.500 --> 01:25:45.890
The children of these
unions frequently identify

01:25:45.890 --> 01:25:47.970
with both parts of their heritage.

01:25:47.970 --> 01:25:51.120 position:56%
Furthermore, children of black
immigrants born in the United States

01:25:51.120 --> 01:25:54.490
or brought here as young
children, more often than not,

01:25:54.490 --> 01:25:55.790
think of themselves

01:25:55.790 --> 01:25:58.180
as African-Americans
in different context.

01:25:58.180 --> 01:26:01.920
Identifying with that-- Sometimes
identifying with that culture often

01:26:01.920 --> 01:26:04.460
with some resistance
from their parents.

01:26:04.460 --> 01:26:06.110
However, the American-born children

01:26:06.110 --> 01:26:08.610
of African immigrants have
often been most successful

01:26:08.610 --> 01:26:12.570
at understanding American society
than their parents have as evident

01:26:12.570 --> 01:26:16.540
in their increased participation
in civic and political issues.

01:26:16.540 --> 01:26:20.750
Recent events have highlighted
these commonalities and of course,

01:26:20.750 --> 01:26:24.430
the most high profile
one was the 1999 shooting

01:26:24.430 --> 01:26:28.710
of the Guinean immigrant Amadou
Diallo where African-Americans--

01:26:28.710 --> 01:26:32.560
activists rallied around
African immigrants.

01:26:32.560 --> 01:26:35.310
And more recently, many
African immigrants,

01:26:35.310 --> 01:26:37.950
particularly of the younger
generation have been involved

01:26:37.950 --> 01:26:39.890
in the Black Lives Matter movement.

01:26:39.890 --> 01:26:43.140
More formal ties and
connections are also being created

01:26:43.140 --> 01:26:45.840
between African-Americans
and black immigrants.

01:26:45.840 --> 01:26:47.710
Just as Booker T. Washington spoke

01:26:47.710 --> 01:26:52.230
out against the 1915
immigration bill, in 2006,

01:26:52.230 --> 01:26:55.720
a group of black American and black
African immigrants came together

01:26:55.720 --> 01:27:00.450
in Oakland, California to form the
Black Alliance for Just Immigration

01:27:00.450 --> 01:27:04.110
to "support the demands of
the immigrant rights movement

01:27:04.110 --> 01:27:08.900 position:56%
and to engage African-Americans in
a dialog about the underlying issues

01:27:08.900 --> 01:27:14.140
of race and economic status that
frame US immigration policy."

01:27:14.140 --> 01:27:16.100
The relationship between
blacks and--

01:27:16.100 --> 01:27:20.580
from Africa and African-Americans
has been long and continuous.

01:27:20.580 --> 01:27:23.380
Since the late 19th
and early 20th century,

01:27:23.380 --> 01:27:26.500
black immigrants have been
arriving in the United States.

01:27:26.500 --> 01:27:30.360 position:56%
Although at times they may have seem
invisible to the largest society,

01:27:30.360 --> 01:27:32.280
black immigrants were
never invisible

01:27:32.280 --> 01:27:36.410
to African-Americans among whom
they settled, worked, married,

01:27:36.410 --> 01:27:39.970
and who were often their
entry point into the society.

01:27:39.970 --> 01:27:43.050
Although in adjusting to American
society they have experienced

01:27:43.050 --> 01:27:44.930
difficulty in assimilating,

01:27:44.930 --> 01:27:48.420
the presence of an established
native-born black population has

01:27:48.420 --> 01:27:50.870 position:56%
been beneficial to black immigrants.

01:27:50.870 --> 01:27:54.790
As more black immigrants arrive in
the United States, the definition

01:27:54.790 --> 01:27:58.220
of African American will
expand as black immigrants

01:27:58.220 --> 01:28:01.020
and native-born blacks
find common cause.

