01:34:03.580 --> 01:34:05.920
And I had to beg her to stay.

01:34:05.920 --> 01:34:09.150
She thought I was going to
accuse those living outside

01:34:09.150 --> 01:34:11.720
of the continent of not being
authentic in their work.

01:34:11.720 --> 01:34:14.780
And so the only way to
answer the question,

01:34:14.780 --> 01:34:18.470
what is an African author would
have to be someone who grew

01:34:18.470 --> 01:34:20.820
up in Africa and who lives there.

01:34:20.820 --> 01:34:24.440
Such an answer today would
disqualify a very large number

01:34:24.440 --> 01:34:28.650
of those considered major
African authors or filmmakers.

01:34:28.650 --> 01:34:32.360
True, we are all made into
something different when we travel,

01:34:32.360 --> 01:34:35.630
and especially live abroad.

01:34:35.630 --> 01:34:41.130
True, the notion of authenticity or
autochthony is an anthropological

01:34:41.130 --> 01:34:45.260
and political term grounded
in outsider points of view.

01:34:45.260 --> 01:34:49.330
That is those on the outside
trying to define who is an insider

01:34:49.330 --> 01:34:53.160
and where the inside and
outside begins where it ends.

01:34:53.160 --> 01:34:55.580 position:56%
This is, as Johannes Fabian puts it,

01:34:55.580 --> 01:34:58.680
a colonial anthropological
understanding.

01:34:58.680 --> 01:35:04.660
I detest authenticity, the word
and concept, the police who tried

01:35:04.660 --> 01:35:07.450
to define it and especially
those in Africa

01:35:07.450 --> 01:35:11.020
for whom it is the test
of genuineness or not.

01:35:11.020 --> 01:35:14.150
So I was embarrassed that
she took my question so hard

01:35:14.150 --> 01:35:18.350
and I made every effort to reassure
her I meant something different.

01:35:18.350 --> 01:35:20.810
Well, what did I mean?

01:35:20.810 --> 01:35:24.710
These days, I see large swathes of
African culture as being created

01:35:24.710 --> 01:35:27.930
by those living abroad, from
Elach Nusani [assumed spelling]

01:35:27.930 --> 01:35:34.350
to Chris Abani to Pius Adesanmi,
Aminatta Forna, Chimamanda Adichie,

01:35:34.350 --> 01:35:36.530
just as I may-- might have listed--

01:35:36.530 --> 01:35:41.820
might have listed Achebe in past
years, not to mention, Teju Cole

01:35:41.820 --> 01:35:46.080
or Binyavanga Wainaina
and our own Toyin Falola.

01:35:46.080 --> 01:35:49.240
This is not to say that an
even greater contribution

01:35:49.240 --> 01:35:53.140
to African cultural production is
not being created on the continent.

01:35:53.140 --> 01:35:55.870
But those whose works are
likely to enter onto the stage

01:35:55.870 --> 01:35:59.280
of world literature or cinema
are largely living abroad.

01:35:59.280 --> 01:36:01.040
And this is not new.

01:36:01.040 --> 01:36:03.770
But it's testimony to
a changing context.

01:36:03.770 --> 01:36:07.090
And I would argue now that the
literature of Taiye Selasi,

01:36:07.090 --> 01:36:11.150
of Helen Oyeyemi, or NoViolet
Bulawayo, to mention three

01:36:11.150 --> 01:36:14.600
of the most prominent women authors
is radically different from that

01:36:14.600 --> 01:36:18.030 position:56%
of women publishing on the continent
and especially women authors

01:36:18.030 --> 01:36:21.600
of the past, like Flora
Nwapa, Mariama Ba,

01:36:21.600 --> 01:36:25.260
or even Buchi Emecheta whose
own life had been marked

01:36:25.260 --> 01:36:27.250
by beginning her career as an expat

01:36:27.250 --> 01:36:30.670
in London before returning
to Nigeria.

01:36:30.670 --> 01:36:34.820
From the outset, the great
Cameroonian author Ferdinand Oyono

01:36:34.820 --> 01:36:37.680
was living in France and
writing Une vie de boy,

01:36:37.680 --> 01:36:40.940
when Camara Laye was writing
L'Enfant noir in Paris

01:36:40.940 --> 01:36:44.870
and when Senghor and Sedar were
composing their poems in Paris,

01:36:44.870 --> 01:36:48.170
it was common for African authors
to have traveled and lived abroad

01:36:48.170 --> 01:36:51.140
where they pen much
of their early works.

01:36:51.140 --> 01:36:52.900
But that was a different time.

01:36:52.900 --> 01:36:54.630
Their crafts were marked
by an upbringing

01:36:54.630 --> 01:36:57.380
in a world radically
different from today's.

01:36:57.380 --> 01:37:01.010
Marked by colonial or
neocolonial culture and milieu,

01:37:01.010 --> 01:37:03.810
today's African authors
and [inaudible] often live

01:37:03.810 --> 01:37:06.370
in Paris and London and New York.

01:37:06.370 --> 01:37:09.170
Life and culture abroad
remains radically different

01:37:09.170 --> 01:37:12.700
from what is accessible to
Africans living at home.

01:37:12.700 --> 01:37:16.170
It isn't that African culture
isn't being diffused abroad

01:37:16.170 --> 01:37:19.380
but the flows are highly uneven.

01:37:19.380 --> 01:37:23.090
Some like Abani turned to totally
new directions of expression.

01:37:23.090 --> 01:37:26.000
Abani now calls himself a
writer, not an African writer.

01:37:26.000 --> 01:37:30.590
And his writing shares little with
those writing on the continent.

01:37:30.590 --> 01:37:34.320 position:56%
Others can live in New York's little
Senegal or London's Peckham Rye,

01:37:34.320 --> 01:37:38.410
eat their thieboudienne or
poulet yassa every night.

01:37:38.410 --> 01:37:41.900
Youssou N'Dour's concert in Bercy
is completely unlike the one

01:37:41.900 --> 01:37:45.500
in his home club in
Thiossane, Dakar.

01:37:45.500 --> 01:37:46.800
The food abroad for all

01:37:46.800 --> 01:37:50.280
of us doesn't taste the
same as it does at home.

01:37:50.280 --> 01:37:53.290
The music depends on its
audience for the performance

01:37:53.290 --> 01:37:56.150
to acquire its full flavor.

01:37:56.150 --> 01:37:59.200
What is ordinary at home
becomes exotic abroad.

01:37:59.200 --> 01:38:00.940
And even when the name is the same,

01:38:00.940 --> 01:38:04.450
the ingredients can
never be identical.

01:38:04.450 --> 01:38:08.890
All of these presupposes a static
culture which is never the case.

01:38:08.890 --> 01:38:12.120
The cook in New York might wind
up getting all the right flavors

01:38:12.120 --> 01:38:14.820
of pepper soup, only
to learn that the chefs

01:38:14.820 --> 01:38:19.310
in Lagos have found a better way
to make the fish taste spicy.

01:38:19.310 --> 01:38:21.350
Something new is happening.

01:38:21.350 --> 01:38:22.950
There are new conditions
of production,

01:38:22.950 --> 01:38:25.010
new times, new people on the scene.

01:38:25.010 --> 01:38:29.000
We are three generations away from
the early writers of the '50s.

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:32.270
Try to imagine what the
Biafran war meant for Achebe.

01:38:32.270 --> 01:38:37.790
In his memoir, there was a country,
a personal history of Biafra.

01:38:37.790 --> 01:38:41.420
He takes, which he wrote
in 2012, he takes us back

01:38:41.420 --> 01:38:45.720
to a late British colonial
period before independence.

01:38:45.720 --> 01:38:48.890
In a radical revision
of his early fiction,

01:38:48.890 --> 01:38:51.080
he tells us the British
rule is a lot better

01:38:51.080 --> 01:38:53.630
than we imagined it to have been.

01:38:53.630 --> 01:38:55.740
Readers raised on "Things
Fall Apart"

01:38:55.740 --> 01:38:58.480
and its truths must have
been astonished to read this,

01:38:58.480 --> 01:39:02.630
Achebe with age turning more
indulgent had done so much

01:39:02.630 --> 01:39:05.550
to shape our thinking about
those early missionaries

01:39:05.550 --> 01:39:08.570
and administrators as
arrogant and small minded

01:39:08.570 --> 01:39:11.840
and had given generations
a clear understanding

01:39:11.840 --> 01:39:13.850
of Eurocentric colonial thought.

01:39:13.850 --> 01:39:16.700
The adjustment is difficult.

01:39:16.700 --> 01:39:19.970
Many of today's African
writers are in fact mixed race.

01:39:19.970 --> 01:39:23.560
When Achebe and Emecheta and
[inaudible] wrote about Biafra,

01:39:23.560 --> 01:39:29.730
none of them could have imagined a
heroine like Kainene in Adichie's

01:39:29.730 --> 01:39:36.440 position:56%
"Half Yellow Sun" whose elegance and
standoffishness redefined the image

01:39:36.440 --> 01:39:38.730
of the African urban sophisticate.

01:39:38.730 --> 01:39:40.210
It's Kainene I'm talking about.

01:39:40.210 --> 01:39:43.080
You could say that about
Adichie too if you want.

01:39:43.080 --> 01:39:44.750
She didn't care a whit.

01:39:44.750 --> 01:39:46.050
That is Kainene now.

01:39:46.050 --> 01:39:50.300
Did not care a whit for something
called evil cultural politics

01:39:50.300 --> 01:39:52.110
and the character in the novel.

01:39:52.110 --> 01:39:56.010
Instead she gave herself to a
struggle despite her wealthy

01:39:56.010 --> 01:39:57.570
and privileged upbringing.

01:39:57.570 --> 01:39:59.990
She married a white man,
a character the likes

01:39:59.990 --> 01:40:02.480
of whom it would be
impossible to find

01:40:02.480 --> 01:40:05.530
in the first two generations
of African literature.

01:40:05.530 --> 01:40:07.600
If there is a single
story of the African

01:40:07.600 --> 01:40:10.730
which Europeans have been
constructing for centuries,

01:40:10.730 --> 01:40:14.520
simultaneously there is a
single story of the European

01:40:14.520 --> 01:40:17.300
which Africans have
also constructed.

01:40:17.300 --> 01:40:21.280
That construction dissolves
as Adichie creates characters

01:40:21.280 --> 01:40:24.200
like the Englishman
Richard whose engagement

01:40:24.200 --> 01:40:27.950
with Nigerian Kainene
somehow led him

01:40:27.950 --> 01:40:30.770 position:56%
to embrace a new form of commitment.

01:40:30.770 --> 01:40:34.280
One not at all like what have
been required for those engaged

01:40:34.280 --> 01:40:37.240
in the original struggle
for national liberation

01:40:37.240 --> 01:40:40.440
as it had been during the
period of imperialism.

01:40:40.440 --> 01:40:45.530
Now, the struggle entailed a new
configuration of national economy

01:40:45.530 --> 01:40:49.090
like that of Eritrea,
South Sudan or Biafra,

01:40:49.090 --> 01:40:52.050 position:56%
for whom seeking independent freedom

01:40:52.050 --> 01:40:55.160
from the autocratic
sometimes brutal state whose

01:40:55.160 --> 01:40:57.850
by politics have reshaped
what's used

01:40:57.850 --> 01:41:01.220
to be called [foreign
language] commitment.

01:41:01.220 --> 01:41:04.070
Biafra was in fact the harbinger.

01:41:04.070 --> 01:41:08.820
The language of the new freedom
fighter, not only the new African

01:41:08.820 --> 01:41:13.150
but the new Afro-European comes
with Richard whose encounter

01:41:13.150 --> 01:41:16.880 position:56%
with other white foreigners
discombobulates their binary notions

01:41:16.880 --> 01:41:19.720
of "us" and "them"
as he plays his role

01:41:19.720 --> 01:41:22.730 position:56%
as official spokesperson for Biafra.

01:41:22.730 --> 01:41:26.390
Here's a fragment of the novelist's
depiction of Richard's encounter

01:41:26.390 --> 01:41:28.880
with two white American
journalists who come

01:41:28.880 --> 01:41:32.100
to Port Harcourt for their story.

01:41:32.100 --> 01:41:35.580
"Richard was not sure how long they
had waited before boarding their

01:41:35.580 --> 01:41:38.940
flight at Lisbon, but the wait
at Sao Tome for a relief flight

01:41:38.940 --> 01:41:41.420
to Biafra had stretched 17 hours.

01:41:41.420 --> 01:41:42.910
They needed a bath.

01:41:42.910 --> 01:41:44.570
When the plump one,
sitting next to Richard,

01:41:44.570 --> 01:41:48.300
began to talk about his first
visit to Biafra at the beginning

01:41:48.300 --> 01:41:51.860
of the war, Richard thought
he needed a mouthwash too."

01:41:51.860 --> 01:41:55.300
As we get the back story of
Richard's role in escorting them,

01:41:55.300 --> 01:41:57.340
we're provided more
and more material

01:41:57.340 --> 01:41:59.170
that signifies their difference

01:41:59.170 --> 01:42:03.640
where Richard has become
one of us and less of them.

01:42:03.640 --> 01:42:05.300
"Richard disliked him.

01:42:05.300 --> 01:42:09.290
He disliked his washed-out green
eyes and his red-freckled face.

01:42:09.290 --> 01:42:12.300 position:56%
When he had met them at the
airport and handed them their passes

01:42:12.300 --> 01:42:14.370
and told them he would
be their guide

01:42:14.370 --> 01:42:16.820
and that the Biafran
government welcomed them,

01:42:16.820 --> 01:42:20.310
