expression of scornful amusement.

01:42:20.310 --> 01:42:26.330 position:56%
It was as if he was saying, 'You are
speaking for the Biafrans?'" We need

01:42:26.330 --> 01:42:29.400
to remember how Cesaire
problematized his own youthful

01:42:29.400 --> 01:42:33.660 position:56%
arrogance in thinking he could speak
for his people in Fort-de-France

01:42:33.660 --> 01:42:36.870
and set that against this
reinvented global figure

01:42:36.870 --> 01:42:41.120
of a spokesperson in
a post-colonial age.

01:42:41.120 --> 01:42:43.990
Richard's whiteness changes
with his [foreign language]

01:42:43.990 --> 01:42:47.830
but [foreign language] too has
changed radically into something

01:42:47.830 --> 01:42:51.660
that we now express in terms
of the globally complex.

01:42:51.660 --> 01:42:55.360
It's to be found not in the white
American journalist scornful retort

01:42:55.360 --> 01:42:59.680
"you" speaking for the Biafrans
but rather than narrative itself

01:42:59.680 --> 01:43:05.200
that prepares us to accept
Richard's reflective self-awareness

01:43:05.200 --> 01:43:09.260 position:56%
as he judges the failures of the
two American's paltry understandings

01:43:09.260 --> 01:43:11.340
of his situation.

01:43:11.340 --> 01:43:14.660
This self-awareness translates
into his ability to put himself

01:43:14.660 --> 01:43:18.850
in their position so as
to judge its inadequacies.

01:43:18.850 --> 01:43:22.310
This is mirrored in Adichie's
ability to put herself

01:43:22.310 --> 01:43:24.790
into her white roommate's shoes

01:43:24.790 --> 01:43:27.580
in her famous TED Talk
on the single story.

01:43:27.580 --> 01:43:31.130 position:56%
Or, in the shoes of her white
character, Richard, who can also see

01:43:31.130 --> 01:43:35.720
and judge the perspective of his
fellow white racist journalists.

01:43:35.720 --> 01:43:42.040
Does the skin color still
function to create compatriots?

01:43:42.040 --> 01:43:45.540
Not so much in Adichie's
constructions.

01:43:45.540 --> 01:43:47.970
Other wonderfully constructed
white characters appear

01:43:47.970 --> 01:43:51.380
in recent fiction like, Aminatta
Forna's "Memories of Love".

01:43:51.380 --> 01:43:55.770
Where the British Dr. Adrian
has become an inverted Bintou,

01:43:55.770 --> 01:43:59.740
one who Sierra Leone has generated
and prolonged the longer he stays

01:43:59.740 --> 01:44:02.500
in Africa, in love with Mamakay.

01:44:02.500 --> 01:44:04.260
His and Richard's discourses
are new.

01:44:04.260 --> 01:44:06.280
Their complexity more compelling

01:44:06.280 --> 01:44:08.900
than the more one-sided
representation

01:44:08.900 --> 01:44:13.560
of white expat experts seen
in Soyinka's early novel,

01:44:13.560 --> 01:44:16.790
"The Interpreters", or Achebe's
white characters in "Anthills

01:44:16.790 --> 01:44:21.780
of the Savannah", Dick with Mad
Medico, who still quotes Lord Acton

01:44:21.780 --> 01:44:25.760
in establishing his difference
from colonials of the past.

01:44:25.760 --> 01:44:28.370
For me, he's part of
another single story

01:44:28.370 --> 01:44:30.890
like the white stereotype
figures of Mr. Brown

01:44:30.890 --> 01:44:34.420
and Reverend Smith in
"Things Fall Apart".

01:44:34.420 --> 01:44:37.910
In the Adichie and Forna novels,
the native guy now takes the form

01:44:37.910 --> 01:44:42.470
of enamored white men like
Richard who are positioned as "us"

01:44:42.470 --> 01:44:47.640
and "them" as figures who are
more than hybrid but now double.

01:44:47.640 --> 01:44:53.700 position:56%
They simultaneously are us and them
or at least partly so for as we all,

01:44:53.700 --> 01:44:58.110
in fact, inhabit multiple
subjectivities.

01:44:58.110 --> 01:45:02.000
In "The Thing around My
Neck", Adichie writes a story

01:45:02.000 --> 01:45:05.360
about a Nigerian wife who joins
her husband in New Jersey.

01:45:05.360 --> 01:45:09.350 position:56%
Nkem raises the kids in the states
while Obiora commutes back and forth

01:45:09.350 --> 01:45:14.520
to home in Africa and has a second
bureau as they call it in Lagos.

01:45:14.520 --> 01:45:17.250
Nkem meanwhile has
become Americanized.

01:45:17.250 --> 01:45:19.910
This is how Adichie puts it.

01:45:19.910 --> 01:45:24.610
"She really belonged to this county
now, this country of curiosities

01:45:24.610 --> 01:45:27.160
and crudities, this country
where you could drive at night

01:45:27.160 --> 01:45:29.090
and not fear armed robbers,

01:45:29.090 --> 01:45:33.450
where restaurants serve one
person enough food for three."

01:45:33.450 --> 01:45:35.950
Still, she missed home.

01:45:35.950 --> 01:45:39.220
Home is conveyed through the
familiar ties of family and friends

01:45:39.220 --> 01:45:42.200 position:56%
of language and the music of speech.

01:45:42.200 --> 01:45:45.010
But it's the immediacy of
the physical environment

01:45:45.010 --> 01:45:49.110
that brings her home
to her this difference.

01:45:49.110 --> 01:45:52.600
"And when the snow covers the
yellow fire hydrant on the street,

01:45:52.600 --> 01:45:56.990
she misses the Lagos sun that
glares down even when it rains.

01:45:56.990 --> 01:45:58.980
She has sometimes thought
about moving back home

01:45:58.980 --> 01:46:01.700
but never seriously,
never concretely.

01:46:01.700 --> 01:46:05.520
She goes to a Pilates class twice
a week in Philly with her neighbor.

01:46:05.520 --> 01:46:07.730
She bakes cookies for
her children's classes

01:46:07.730 --> 01:46:09.690
and hers are always the favorites.

01:46:09.690 --> 01:46:12.330 position:56%
She expects banks to have drive-ins.

01:46:12.330 --> 01:46:16.720
America has grown on her, snaked
its roots under her skin."

01:46:16.720 --> 01:46:19.160
I like that last sentence a lot.

01:46:19.160 --> 01:46:23.450
Adichie is sensitive to the
registers of accent, culture, food,

01:46:23.450 --> 01:46:26.470
gender relations, taste,
and contemporary styles

01:46:26.470 --> 01:46:28.760
that constitute the
American presence.

01:46:28.760 --> 01:46:32.330
And her language records them in
her double consciousness at times

01:46:32.330 --> 01:46:35.550
with ironic tones, but more
often in sheep pastures

01:46:35.550 --> 01:46:38.840
and idiomatic turnings of the
phrase that render the perfect--

01:46:38.840 --> 01:46:40.450
the portrait so perfectly

01:46:40.450 --> 01:46:43.830
as to suture the native-born
American reader

01:46:43.830 --> 01:46:48.290
into the African narrator's
perspective occluding the

01:46:48.290 --> 01:46:53.340
non-narrative position, excuse me,
occluding the nonnative position

01:46:53.340 --> 01:46:55.980
of the narrative subjectivity.

01:46:55.980 --> 01:46:59.960
I'm using the cinematic term suture
to signify the identification

01:46:59.960 --> 01:47:03.980
of the spectator with the character
on the screen as specifically

01:47:03.980 --> 01:47:06.410
with the character's point of view.

01:47:06.410 --> 01:47:10.050
This is accomplished in film by
positioning the camera in the place

01:47:10.050 --> 01:47:14.010 position:56%
of the actor so that we can
experience what the character feels,

01:47:14.010 --> 01:47:17.780
fears, loves and especially
sees or doesn't see.

01:47:17.780 --> 01:47:20.270
The techniques for moving
that suture from one character

01:47:20.270 --> 01:47:24.090
to another involve camera placement
and movement as in the shot,

01:47:24.090 --> 01:47:27.490
counter shot where two characters
speaking to each other are viewed

01:47:27.490 --> 01:47:29.990
from the position of
their interlocutors

01:47:29.990 --> 01:47:33.290
with whose perspective
we come to identify.

01:47:33.290 --> 01:47:36.410
Who are we at that moment
of suture when we let go

01:47:36.410 --> 01:47:39.660
of our own real position
in the theaters?

01:47:39.660 --> 01:47:41.350
We pass in the moment of suture

01:47:41.350 --> 01:47:46.200
into what Lacan calls
meconnaissance or misrecognition.

01:47:46.200 --> 01:47:47.650
Because it constitutes us

01:47:47.650 --> 01:47:51.560 position:56%
as gathering together the fragmented
pieces of knowledge that we hold

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:56.630
of ourselves, especially those
pieces reflected back to us

01:47:56.630 --> 01:48:00.760
in the eyes of others, whose name
for us we might wish to accept

01:48:00.760 --> 01:48:04.380
as our own and thus
to identify with.

01:48:04.380 --> 01:48:08.730
These moments of fragile and fraud
with the perils of being disrupted

01:48:08.730 --> 01:48:12.880
by a name calling, we might
not wish to acknowledge.

01:48:12.880 --> 01:48:16.450
It's most telling for the immigrant
who goes so far as to change,

01:48:16.450 --> 01:48:21.110
not only her homeland but
also her home, her home boys,

01:48:21.110 --> 01:48:26.730
her girlfriends, family, language,
status and ultimately name itself.

01:48:26.730 --> 01:48:32.050
Call me John, not John
Pierre, Jack, not jackamo,

01:48:32.050 --> 01:48:36.810
Joe not Juso, or Feller not fella.

01:48:36.810 --> 01:48:40.410
What is retained here
is the new identity

01:48:40.410 --> 01:48:43.120
which then obscures what's
responsible for making

01:48:43.120 --> 01:48:46.630
that identity in giving it reality.

01:48:46.630 --> 01:48:48.310
This is the ultimate
goal of the suture.

01:48:48.310 --> 01:48:53.330 position:56%
Its act of violence in accomplishing
the act of identification for those

01:48:53.330 --> 01:48:57.770
who take themselves to be American,
Nigerian, Senegalese or French,

01:48:57.770 --> 01:49:01.290
to be the holder of the green
card while occluding the presence

01:49:01.290 --> 01:49:05.270
of the camera that captures the
eye of the spectator or that

01:49:05.270 --> 01:49:09.200
of the narrative that
enchants the ear of the rear.

01:49:09.200 --> 01:49:12.420
The violence that springs from
this assumption of oneness

01:49:12.420 --> 01:49:16.500 position:56%
in the suture consists in forgetting
the violence involved in the act

01:49:16.500 --> 01:49:21.000
of constituting oneself
as one, as authentic.

01:49:21.000 --> 01:49:25.730
The suturing of the subject in the
Caine awardee Binyavanga Wainaina's

01:49:25.730 --> 01:49:28.750
"One Day I Will Write About
This Place" is complicated

01:49:28.750 --> 01:49:32.720
by the radical violence that marks
the narrator's conflictual diaspora

01:49:32.720 --> 01:49:34.710
sites of enunciation.

01:49:34.710 --> 01:49:36.010
At one moment in the text,

01:49:36.010 --> 01:49:38.240
he describes taking
the Hudson Line train

01:49:38.240 --> 01:49:41.620
into the city while Togo is
playing in the World Cup.

01:49:41.620 --> 01:49:43.510
Eyadema's corrupt family
has been put

01:49:43.510 --> 01:49:46.750
